04345nam a22005535i 9780520961685DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209616857 a10.1515/97805209616852doi  a(DE-B1597)539703  a(OCoLC)923818582  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPK6451.B73 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a962.404/32231 aKinra, Rajeev, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWriting Self, Writing Empire :bChandar Bhan Brahman and the Cultural World of the Indo-Persian State Secretary /cRajeev Kinra. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (394 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouth Asia Across the Disciplines00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. A Hindu Secretary in King Shah Jahan's Court -- t1 Chandar Bhan's Intellectual World -- t2 A Mirror for Munshīs -- t3 King of Delhi, King of the World -- t4 Writing the Mughal Self -- t5 Making Indo-Persian Literature Fresh -- t6 The Persistence of Gossip -- tConclusion. Ending at Just the Beginning -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aA free ebook version of this title is available through Luminos, University of California Press's new open access publishing program for monographs. Visit www.luminosoa.org to learn more.Writing Self, Writing Empire examines the life, career, and writings of the Mughal state secretary, or munshi, Chandar Bhan "Brahman" (d. c.1670), one of the great Indo-Persian poets and prose stylists of early modern South Asia. Chandar Bhan's life spanned the reigns of four different emperors, Akbar (1556-1605), Jahangir (1605-1627), Shah Jahan (1628-1658), and Aurangzeb 'Alamgir (1658-1707), the last of the "Great Mughals" whose courts dominated the culture and politics of the subcontinent at the height of the empire's power, territorial reach, and global influence. As a high-caste Hindu who worked for a series of Muslim monarchs and other officials, forming powerful friendships along the way, Chandar Bhan's experience bears vivid testimony to the pluralistic atmosphere of the Mughal court, particularly during the reign of Shah Jahan, the celebrated builder of the Taj Mahal. But his widely circulated and emulated works also touch on a range of topics central to our understanding of the court's literary, mystical, administrative, and ethical cultures, while his letters and autobiographical writings provide tantalizing examples of early modern Indo-Persian modes of self-fashioning. Chandar Bhan's oeuvre is a valuable window onto a crucial, though surprisingly neglected, period of Mughal cultural and political history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, IndiczMogul EmpirevBiography. 0aPersian literaturezIndiaxHistory and criticism. 0aSecretarieszMogul EmpirevBiography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520961685?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961685zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961685/original  a978-3-11-062111-2 University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA